@incollection{Besson2018,
abstract = {Ecological networks provide a useful abstraction of ecological systems, representing them as graphs, composed of nodes (species) and edges (interactions). This formalism allows to use a whole set of measures, extended from graph theory, to study ecological systems. In this article, we review some of the most prominent findings and areas of research from the last decade. We start by reviewing how it was used to uncover invariance in the organization of ecological systems. Then we show the importance of structure when studying systems dynamics and how this coupled approach sheds new light on emerging properties of ecological systems. Through this chapter we want to highlight the important contribution of networks in clarifying ecosystem properties and functioning, but also the potential to develop new approaches, for example to compare ecosystems and to relate species traits to community structure.},
